The Macedonian people voted in a referendum on Sunday if they wanted to change their name to "Republic of North Macedonia," a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece and block applications for admission to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the majority of Macedonia's Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign raised doubts about whether the result will reach the minimum 50 percent required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot was: “Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for admission to entities such as the EU or NATO from Macedonia, one of the emerging countries of the fall of Yugoslavia.
"Today I came to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, several members of parliament said they would abide by the result of the vote and would make it final.
The change of nine would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission stated that at 1 p.m. there would be no irregularities.
However, the turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent of the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters cast their vote.
