Information about the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the most recent report by the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Conservation Commission, a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area is occurring.
According to the commission, increasingly unequal conditions are being observed in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which may mean that concentrations are decreasing.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern counties of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Concentrations can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsboroug County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
Medium-level concentrations were reported on the coast or off the coast of Pinellas County last week, background and elevated concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, background and intermediate-level concentrations on the coast of the county of Leigh and Charlotte County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation are reported to continue.
No such incidents have been reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
